{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"958ad26b-f43f-46a3-9f48-5eee2f04d2c4","content":"This is a TUnit project running on Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` syntax rather than VSTest `--filter`. The command is:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter pattern is `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>` — using `*` wildcards for everything except the class name targets just `SmsNotificationTests`.\n\n> **Note:** TUnit projects are `Exe`-based MTP apps, so `dotnet run` is the preferred way to execute them. If you must use `dotnet test`, use:\n> ```\n> dotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n> ```\n> (the `--` separates dotnet test args from MTP args).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"669744fd-c068-4dde-94d1-fe59e79f94b6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, you use `--treenode-filter` to filter tests. To filter by class name, the syntax would be:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nWait, TUnit projects use `OutputType: Exe` and run via `dotnet run`. But the user asked about `dotnet test`. Let me think about this.\n\nTUnit 0.6.x uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform. With MTP, `dotnet test` should work but the filter syntax differs. For MTP-based runners, `dotnet test` passes through to the MTP runner.\n \nWith `dotnet test`, the `--filter` option gets translated to the underlying MTP platform, so filtering by class name would look like using the standard MTP filter syntax. The `--filter` flag should work with TUnit's MTP integration when running through `dotnet test`.","outputTokens":743,"requestId":"6800:228DD8:2C6B718:3103467:69FD3DFD"},"id":"27920ec9-b9cd-40aa-a4a8-8295a75907b6","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:36:14.782Z","parentId":"21a94f89-b